WEBVTT

00:00.667 --> 00:02.501
             [♪♪♪]

00:02.503 --> 00:03.602
[DOORBELL RINGS]

00:03.604 --> 00:04.903
        [RAZOR BUZZING]

00:07.475 --> 00:09.475
        [DOORBELL RINGS]

00:18.919 --> 00:20.118
[RAZOR BUZZING]
           Master?

00:20.120 --> 00:21.587
        [DOORBELL RINGS]

00:29.730 --> 00:31.463
                 Hello, my name
               is Harry Huggins.

00:31.465 --> 00:32.965
           Is Major Nelson home?

00:32.967 --> 00:36.234
 Oh, yes, but he--
He's, uh, occupied.

00:36.236 --> 00:37.803
                  You're, uh,
                  Mrs. Nelson?

00:37.805 --> 00:40.238
          Oh, not yet,
     but I am very hopeful.

00:40.240 --> 00:43.542
  Oh, Major Nelson
is quite fond of me.

00:43.544 --> 00:46.478
  I am his, uh, housekeeper.

00:46.480 --> 00:47.579
               Yes.

00:47.581 --> 00:50.048
        Well, uh, may I wait
         for Major Nelson?

00:50.050 --> 00:52.851
        Oh, certainly.
       Please, come in.

00:52.853 --> 00:54.052
           Thank you.

00:57.558 --> 01:00.058
Tiny, little place,
     isn't it?

01:00.060 --> 01:02.260
                  Tiny?
       Boxy.

01:02.262 --> 01:04.897
They don't build houses
 the way they used to.

01:04.899 --> 01:06.798
             Pity.

01:06.800 --> 01:08.400
             No taste.

01:08.402 --> 01:10.702
    Major Nelson
has wonderful taste.

01:10.704 --> 01:12.303
               Uh-huh.

01:12.305 --> 01:15.273
       Grand Rapids Renaissance.

01:15.275 --> 01:17.943
     You must see
the rest of the house.

01:17.945 --> 01:19.945
             [♪♪♪]

01:26.186 --> 01:27.418
               Why that--

01:27.420 --> 01:29.454
That looks like
  a Louis XV.

01:29.456 --> 01:31.389
                      Oh, it is.

01:31.391 --> 01:33.491
Why, it must
be worth a fortune.

01:33.493 --> 01:35.126
            Oh, yes.

01:35.128 --> 01:38.063
      Money means nothing
        to Major Nelson.

01:49.976 --> 01:52.911
                 That's a copy
                 of a Renoir.

01:54.014 --> 01:55.747
         It is no copy.

01:55.749 --> 01:59.150
         A real Renoir?

01:59.152 --> 02:00.919
          In Cocoa Beach?

02:01.454 --> 02:03.255
           Of course.

02:10.598 --> 02:15.000
       Uh, be careful of Major
     Nelson's genuine Ming vase.

02:16.336 --> 02:18.103
      Ming vase?

02:18.105 --> 02:21.673
         I told you Major Nelson
           has wonderful taste.

02:21.675 --> 02:24.676
  Does he keep any cash
      in the house?

02:24.678 --> 02:26.311
                    Cash?

02:26.313 --> 02:27.946
                 [GIGGLES]

02:27.948 --> 02:30.882
      That safe is full of cash.

02:33.287 --> 02:36.054
           Full of cash?
                     Mm-hm.

02:42.496 --> 02:44.929
    It's like a museum.

02:44.931 --> 02:47.199
     Do you take care
 of this house yourself?

02:47.201 --> 02:51.269
            Oh, no. Major Nelson
             has many servants.

02:55.242 --> 02:57.242
             [♪♪♪]

03:01.348 --> 03:03.281
Uh, no, thank you.

03:03.283 --> 03:05.617
       The others are off today.

03:07.921 --> 03:10.155
                  No, thank you.
                   Good morning.

03:10.157 --> 03:12.991
       Oh, good morning, master.

03:12.993 --> 03:14.325
           You have a visitor.

03:14.327 --> 03:15.961
     Major Nelson.
                        Huh?

03:15.963 --> 03:17.162
I'm Harry Huggins.

03:17.164 --> 03:18.964
Department of Internal Revenue.

03:20.400 --> 03:21.733
             [♪♪♪]

03:23.771 --> 03:25.771
             [♪♪♪]

04:13.086 --> 04:15.086
             [♪♪♪]

04:19.659 --> 04:21.493
      I-I'm sorry, d-did you say

04:21.495 --> 04:23.761
               the Department
            of Internal Revenue?
    Yes.

04:23.763 --> 04:27.298
I have a refund here for you
on your last year's income tax.

04:27.300 --> 04:29.434
Seventeen dollars
and fifty cents.

04:29.436 --> 04:30.902
           Since I live
       in the neighborhood,

04:30.904 --> 04:33.137
          I just thought
      I'd drop it by myself.

04:33.139 --> 04:34.706
                Well, thank you,
                  Mr. Huggins.

04:34.708 --> 04:37.976
    I'll just keep this until
   we finish the investigation.

04:37.978 --> 04:38.976
                  Investigation?

04:38.978 --> 04:40.244
         Major, this house

04:40.246 --> 04:43.415
     is the Cocoa Beach branch
           of the Louvre.

04:44.451 --> 04:45.517
                     [CHUCKLING]
                      I'm sorry.

04:45.519 --> 04:46.718
                   I don't seem
                  to understand.

04:46.720 --> 04:48.553
         Your housekeeper

04:48.555 --> 04:49.821
was kind enough

04:49.823 --> 04:52.490
     to show me your treasures.

04:52.492 --> 04:54.992
                      Oh, I see.
                     What, uh--?

04:54.994 --> 04:57.762
    What treasures were you kind
     enough to show Mr. Huggins?

04:57.764 --> 04:59.230
Oh, you know, master,

04:59.232 --> 05:02.967
  your, uh, Louis XV,
your Renoir, your Ming.

05:02.969 --> 05:04.769
               [LAUGHING]
        Oh! Oh, those treasures.

05:04.771 --> 05:07.371
                    TONY:
             You sure you didn't
               forget anything?

05:08.675 --> 05:09.874
          Oh.

05:10.977 --> 05:12.376
              The statue.

05:13.447 --> 05:16.648
         Is that a Michelangelo?

05:16.650 --> 05:18.316
                     TONY:
                 I wouldn't be
               at all surprised.

05:18.318 --> 05:19.917
          Are you quite through?

05:19.919 --> 05:24.088
I have not had so much fun
 in a long time, master.

05:24.090 --> 05:25.691
Would you like to see
   something else?

05:25.693 --> 05:28.126
            No, I've, uh--
     I've seen more than enough,

05:28.128 --> 05:29.260
thank you.

05:29.262 --> 05:30.962
             I'll be back here
              in the morning

05:30.964 --> 05:32.330
             with the assessor.

05:32.332 --> 05:34.633
                Mr. Huggins, uh,
                  all of this--

05:34.635 --> 05:36.735
                All of this
           is not what it seems.

05:36.737 --> 05:37.969
                    [LAUGHING]
                   Oh, you're--

05:37.971 --> 05:39.271
                 As soon
        as I tell you the truth,

05:39.273 --> 05:40.538
                  you're gonna
                get a big laugh.

05:40.540 --> 05:42.774
        [BOTH LAUGHING]

05:42.776 --> 05:44.809
              Oh, I'm dying
          to hear all about it.

05:44.811 --> 05:47.679
             Well, Jeannie does,
                 uh, these--

05:47.681 --> 05:49.381
     We like to call 'em tricks.

05:49.383 --> 05:50.716
        None of this is genuine.

05:50.718 --> 05:53.184
    Of course it is genuine.
   Would you hold this a moment?

05:53.186 --> 05:54.452
                Yes.
          And stand right there.

05:54.454 --> 05:56.621
       You see, the Michelangelo
             and the Renoir

05:56.623 --> 05:59.157
      and the Ming and whatever,
       well, they're all just--

05:59.159 --> 06:00.458
   Just junk.

06:00.460 --> 06:01.893
[CHUCKLES]

06:01.895 --> 06:03.995
          Well, I'd like to say,
               my guess is,

06:03.997 --> 06:06.297
           this junk's gonna run
             somewhere between

06:06.299 --> 06:09.734
       20 to 30 years in prison.

06:09.736 --> 06:11.870
    Oh, 20 to 30 years.

06:11.872 --> 06:14.973
             And you can explain
              to the government

06:14.975 --> 06:20.344
        why none of it appeared
      on your income tax, major.

06:20.346 --> 06:23.148
        Oh, and I wouldn't touch
        that safe if I were you.

06:23.150 --> 06:24.215
           Safe?

06:24.217 --> 06:26.384
           The one full of cash.

06:26.386 --> 06:27.786
    Oh.

06:27.788 --> 06:29.253
              I'll be back early

06:29.255 --> 06:33.224
                in the morning
              with the assessor.

06:34.861 --> 06:37.662
               We showed him,
            did we not, master?

06:37.664 --> 06:40.665
       I think he was impressed.

06:40.667 --> 06:42.500
What made you do that?

06:42.502 --> 06:44.369
             Why, he did not
        like your house, master.

06:44.371 --> 06:47.038
          And I did not want him
         to think you were poor.

06:47.040 --> 06:50.074
Well, that's what I am,
    a poor master.
                      No.

06:50.076 --> 06:52.544
Yeah, I wake up in the morning
  and I-I come down to br--

06:52.546 --> 06:55.146
       And what do I-I--?
 A Michelangelo. And a Renoir?

06:55.148 --> 06:57.215
       And a Ming.
You gotta get rid of this.

06:57.217 --> 07:00.285
          Oh, but I could not
           do that, master.

07:00.287 --> 07:01.552
         Why not?

07:01.554 --> 07:04.422
           Because I want you
       to have beautiful things.

07:04.424 --> 07:07.259
              You never let me
            do anything for you.

07:07.261 --> 07:08.560
            All the other genies

07:08.562 --> 07:10.595
            give their masters
          treasures and palaces,

07:10.597 --> 07:12.564
              and lovely silks--
   Oh, jeez. I know.

07:12.566 --> 07:16.201
I know, but if I ever need
 a treasure or a palace,

07:16.203 --> 07:18.703
           believe me, you'll be
          the first one to know.

07:18.705 --> 07:21.272
              Well, now, get rid
                of this stuff.

07:21.274 --> 07:22.607
        No.

07:22.609 --> 07:24.943
         Jeannie, I've gotta pay
          income taxes on this.

07:24.945 --> 07:27.078
      But why?
 I gave them to you.

07:27.080 --> 07:28.847
             Well, that doesn't
            make any difference.

07:28.849 --> 07:30.582
                 I still have
             to pay taxes on it.

07:30.584 --> 07:33.351
   You mean people
cannot give you gifts?

07:33.353 --> 07:34.786
             Yeah, that's right.

07:34.788 --> 07:37.121
Oh, you tell your government
    that is ridiculous.

07:37.123 --> 07:38.957
     Ridiculous!

07:38.959 --> 07:40.892
Oh, they are so beautiful.

07:40.894 --> 07:42.293
               Yes, I know that.
          They are--

07:42.295 --> 07:44.563
     They are you.
                   [SIGHS]

07:44.565 --> 07:46.565
       Enjoy them.
                 Yeah, not--

07:46.567 --> 07:48.199
                I-I just--
         I just can't afford it.

07:48.201 --> 07:50.368
          Jeannie? Now, Jeannie,
              you stop that.

07:50.370 --> 07:51.937
               Stop it this--
                  Jeannie!

07:51.939 --> 07:54.372
              Come out of there.
                   Come on.

07:55.341 --> 07:56.641
             Now, listen here,
                young lady.

07:56.643 --> 07:58.710
     I want all this stuff gone,
         you understand that?

07:58.712 --> 08:00.511
          Gone, when I get home.

08:01.682 --> 08:02.747
               Oh...

08:02.749 --> 08:06.417
          He is so adorable
          when he is angry.

08:07.087 --> 08:09.087
             [♪♪♪]

08:11.024 --> 08:14.859
 You mean Jeannie gave you
 a Renoir, a Michelangelo,

08:14.861 --> 08:17.361
   and a Ming vase,
and you're complaining?

08:17.363 --> 08:19.296
Oh, how ungrateful
   can you get?

08:19.298 --> 08:21.499
            Hey, Roger, I gotta
          get rid of that stuff.

08:21.501 --> 08:23.501
     All right. All right.

08:23.503 --> 08:25.003
           What are friends for?

08:25.005 --> 08:26.904
               Tell you what,
           I'll take the Renoir,

08:26.906 --> 08:29.273
       the Michelangelo,
       and the Ming vase.

08:29.275 --> 08:30.875
                 You'll only get
                   in trouble.

08:30.877 --> 08:33.244
Trouble? That's right.
   Get in trouble.

08:33.246 --> 08:34.410
              Uh, tell you what.

08:34.413 --> 08:37.015
            I'll take the Renoir
           and the Michelangelo.

08:37.017 --> 08:38.015
                 No.

08:38.018 --> 08:40.284
How 'bout just the Renoir?
                      No.

08:40.285 --> 08:43.187
Then will you buy me
  a cup of coffee?

08:43.188 --> 08:45.023
                   That I got.

08:45.025 --> 08:46.758
                   Roger,
           don't you understand?

08:46.760 --> 08:49.661
      I am in trouble with
the Internal Revenue Department.

08:49.663 --> 08:51.328
     There's a guy named Huggins
             on my neck.

08:51.330 --> 08:53.131
       He's bringing an assessor
             over tomorrow.

08:53.133 --> 08:55.099
     What am I--? How am I gonna
        explain all that art?

08:55.101 --> 08:57.735
  It's very simple. All you
have to do is tell him that-

08:57.737 --> 08:58.736
               Yeah, what? What?

08:58.738 --> 09:01.372
Well, you could say
    that, uh--

09:01.374 --> 09:02.674
Yeah, you got problems.

09:02.676 --> 09:03.808
Doesn't he always?

09:03.810 --> 09:05.476
What's your problem
 this time, major?

09:05.478 --> 09:07.578
       Nothing, sir. Roger and I
        were talking about art.

09:07.580 --> 09:08.579
        Yeah. About art.

09:08.581 --> 09:10.148
   Tony is a real
  culture vulture.

09:10.150 --> 09:11.182
    [CHUCKLES]

09:11.184 --> 09:12.583
              Yes.

09:12.585 --> 09:14.352
     The simulator's ready
        for you, major.

09:14.354 --> 09:15.420
       I'll be right along, sir.

09:15.422 --> 09:17.088
              You gonna handle
            the ground controls?

09:17.090 --> 09:19.991
It's the least I can do
for one of the great collectors.

09:19.993 --> 09:22.327
If you don't mind, major.
                    Yes, sir.

09:22.329 --> 09:24.562
     You finish this, huh?
                  Huh? Oh, yeah.

09:26.699 --> 09:28.299
Here's your hat.
     Roger?

09:33.006 --> 09:34.238
     How long do I stay up, sir?

09:34.240 --> 09:37.608
     Oh, I think, uh, 60 minutes
          should be plenty.

09:37.610 --> 09:39.310
          Beautiful piece
           of equipment.

09:39.312 --> 09:41.079
        Anything that can happen
             in outer space,

09:41.081 --> 09:42.213
      can happen to you in here.

09:42.215 --> 09:44.082
The only difference is,
it happens in this,

09:44.084 --> 09:45.750
you can get home
in time for lunch.

09:45.752 --> 09:47.118
                 Home for lunch.

09:47.120 --> 09:49.353
       Oh, shall we get started?

09:49.355 --> 09:51.355
             [♪♪♪]

10:05.638 --> 10:07.505
I'm gonna start him
off with some yaw.

10:07.507 --> 10:08.807
      Let's begin at 10 degrees.

10:08.809 --> 10:11.576
   We don't want to shake him up
        too badly at first.

10:16.983 --> 10:18.316
         Are you okay, Tony?

10:18.318 --> 10:20.885
       TONY [OVER RADIO]:
   <i> Fine, here. Let her rip.</i>

10:20.887 --> 10:22.754
Okay, hold tight.

10:22.756 --> 10:24.222
        I'm gonna soup her up.

10:24.224 --> 10:25.389
          <i> I'm ready.</i>

10:38.872 --> 10:40.471
   Give him a 30-degree pitch.

10:40.473 --> 10:41.773
                Yes, sir.

10:45.946 --> 10:47.645
   How you feeling, major?

10:47.647 --> 10:49.614
       <i> Pretty good, sir.</i>

10:56.923 --> 10:59.957
[INHALING & EXHALING]

10:59.959 --> 11:02.427
     Well, you are in remarkably
         good health, major.

11:02.429 --> 11:04.228
        You can get dressed now.
Oh, thanks, sir.

11:04.230 --> 11:06.163
         [PHONE RINGS]
                  Oh, excuse me.

11:08.100 --> 11:09.901
  Dr. Bellows.

11:09.903 --> 11:12.503
A visitor for me?
   Who is it?

11:12.505 --> 11:15.440
    Huggins?
                [GLASS SHATTERS]

11:15.442 --> 11:17.742
I don't know any Huggins.

11:17.744 --> 11:20.210
Oh, urgent, huh?
 Oh, very well.

11:20.212 --> 11:22.947
  I'm on my way
to my office now.

11:22.949 --> 11:24.549
I'll see you later, major.
                   Yes, sir.

11:24.551 --> 11:26.417
  Uh, your shirt.
                     Shirt?

11:26.419 --> 11:27.552
         Uh-uh.

11:27.554 --> 11:29.921
                    Oh, yes.
                   I'm sorry.

11:34.026 --> 11:35.760
              [KNOCKING ON DOOR]
       Oh, come in.

11:36.596 --> 11:38.262
                Dr. Bellows?
Yes.

11:40.266 --> 11:41.365
                  Harry Huggins.

11:41.367 --> 11:43.601
      Mm. Sit down,
       Mr. Huggins.

11:43.603 --> 11:46.003
                 Department
            of Internal Revenue.

11:46.005 --> 11:48.305
Uh, the Department of--?

11:48.307 --> 11:51.642
Now, if it's about that trip
I took to Jamaica last year,

11:51.644 --> 11:53.577
I can prove that it was
 government business.

11:53.579 --> 11:56.548
        I'm not here to, uh,
        discuss you, doctor.

11:56.550 --> 12:00.952
         But, uh, I'll certainly
           make a note of that.

12:01.721 --> 12:03.187
                        Jamaica.

12:04.858 --> 12:08.860
       No, I'm here because
   something peculiar's going on

12:08.862 --> 12:10.962
       with one of your men
           at the base.

12:12.365 --> 12:14.766
What has Major Nelson done now?

12:14.768 --> 12:16.534
    I didn't mention his name.

12:16.536 --> 12:18.035
       How do you know
     it was Major Nelson?

12:18.037 --> 12:19.970
Do you see these reports?

12:19.972 --> 12:22.873
They're all on Major Nelson.

12:22.875 --> 12:24.108
                             Oh?

12:24.110 --> 12:25.776
                  Well, uh,
            what are they about?

12:25.778 --> 12:27.378
Well, I wouldn't know
where to begin.

12:28.348 --> 12:30.114
   Here's a report of a woman

12:30.116 --> 12:33.451
    who swears she saw him
   flying over Cocoa Beach.

12:33.453 --> 12:37.088
   Well, he's a pilot, isn't he?
   What's so unusual about that?

12:37.857 --> 12:39.357
       He had no plane.

12:39.359 --> 12:40.959
                   Oh.

12:40.961 --> 12:44.628
  A gas station attendant
   saw Major Nelson's car

12:44.630 --> 12:46.430
  go into a drive-in theater.

12:47.633 --> 12:49.533
                 Well,
      that doesn't seem unusual.

12:49.535 --> 12:50.534
              Hm.

12:50.536 --> 12:52.103
     No one was in the car.

12:53.339 --> 12:55.172
Oh, here's one
that will interest you.

12:55.174 --> 12:57.574
A witness saw it snow
on Major Nelson's house,

12:57.576 --> 13:00.644
but only on his house,
in the middle of July.

13:00.646 --> 13:02.313
              [LAUGHING]

13:02.315 --> 13:04.748
        That was obviously
          some crackpot.

13:04.750 --> 13:07.851
     It was reported by me,
          Mr. Huggins.

13:08.488 --> 13:09.987
             Oh, was it?

13:09.989 --> 13:11.588
I have a 117 of these.

13:11.590 --> 13:14.992
I'm afraid you'll have
to wait in line.

13:14.994 --> 13:18.095
     The government doesn't wait
           in line, doctor.

13:18.097 --> 13:20.831
     I'm here to get the answers
          to some questions.

13:20.833 --> 13:23.301
Well, I don't know whether
I can answer them, Mr. Huggins.

13:23.303 --> 13:25.602
You see, uh, our files
are confidential.

13:25.604 --> 13:27.471
        I'm with the government,
            remember, doctor?

13:27.473 --> 13:29.340
   Now, that's a coincidence.
            So am I.

13:30.510 --> 13:33.144
        And I'm wearing
     a uniform to prove it.

13:35.348 --> 13:38.716
      How would you like to have
       your income tax audited

13:38.718 --> 13:41.285
      for the last five years?

13:43.289 --> 13:46.290
   How would you
like to be drafted?

13:48.661 --> 13:51.863
      Let me put it another way.

13:51.865 --> 13:56.100
     My branch of the government
    would appreciate cooperation

13:56.102 --> 13:58.702
               from your branch
              of the government.

13:58.704 --> 13:59.904
   What is it
you want to know?

14:01.374 --> 14:07.879
Would you say that Major Nelson
         is a rich man?

14:07.881 --> 14:11.783
     Well, sometimes he is,
    and sometimes he isn't.

14:11.785 --> 14:14.652
        A few weeks ago
       he had $3 million

14:14.654 --> 14:16.654
 in his Christmas club fund.

14:17.456 --> 14:19.557
     His Christmas club fund?

14:19.559 --> 14:22.593
 When we went to track it down,
        it had vanished.

14:23.896 --> 14:26.364
           Well, I think
         I found it again.

14:26.366 --> 14:27.598
            Where?

14:27.600 --> 14:31.803
      Sorry, we can't give out
         that information.

14:33.606 --> 14:36.774
        This is gonna mean
     a nice promotion for me.

14:38.377 --> 14:41.279
       Inspector Huggins.

14:42.748 --> 14:45.850
      We've been after Nelson
          for a long time.

14:45.852 --> 14:47.685
     After him? For what?

14:49.421 --> 14:50.788
   Can you keep it confidential?

14:52.358 --> 14:55.860
     I mean, this is one branch
    of the government talking to

14:55.862 --> 14:58.228
            [WHISPERING]
           another branch
         of the government.

14:58.230 --> 14:59.496
           Go ahead.

14:59.498 --> 15:04.568
         Your Major Nelson
            is the head

15:04.570 --> 15:07.571
         of an international
           smuggling ring.

15:09.008 --> 15:11.008
             [♪♪♪]

15:15.248 --> 15:17.815
     Mr. Huggins, if you told me
          that Major Nelson

15:17.817 --> 15:19.550
          could fly like a bird,

15:19.552 --> 15:23.287
 grow apple trees in the middle
      of his living room,

15:23.289 --> 15:26.858
talk to vacuum cleaners,
I wouldn't argue with you.

15:26.860 --> 15:29.560
    But when you tell me
that you think he's involved

15:29.562 --> 15:31.362
     with an international
      gang of smugglers,

15:31.364 --> 15:34.498
     oh, I'm afraid
I must disagree with you.

15:35.534 --> 15:37.034
               Doctor,

15:40.073 --> 15:44.842
     his salary is $950 a month.

15:45.879 --> 15:49.480
          You show me a man
           who makes that,

15:49.482 --> 15:54.118
       who owns a Michelangelo,
              a Renoir,

15:54.120 --> 15:56.654
       and keeps six servants,

15:56.656 --> 15:58.923
      and I'll show you a crook.

15:58.925 --> 16:02.460
  Major Nelson is not a crook.

16:02.462 --> 16:04.962
  These things are undoubtedly
         reproductions.

16:04.964 --> 16:07.865
        Well, if he reproduced
        the safe full a cash,

16:07.867 --> 16:10.834
        I'm even more anxious
        to get my hands on it.

16:10.836 --> 16:12.303
       That's counterfeiting.

16:13.439 --> 16:15.306
  I've got him coming and going.

16:16.676 --> 16:19.810
    Believe me, it's strange
  to hear myself saying this,

16:19.812 --> 16:22.680
        but I am sure
that Major Nelson is innocent.

16:23.682 --> 16:27.651
          The curator
    of the Palm Beach Museum

16:27.653 --> 16:29.653
is flying up in the morning.

16:29.655 --> 16:34.525
   And, uh, what if Major Nelson
    removes the things tonight?

16:34.527 --> 16:36.393
He'd be a fool if he didn't.

16:36.395 --> 16:37.929
     You mean you think he will?

16:37.931 --> 16:41.666
Of course, doctor.
He's in a panic.

16:41.668 --> 16:43.901
Right at the moment,
the poor devil's out

16:43.903 --> 16:46.571
          probably trying
        to round up a truck.

16:46.573 --> 16:49.006
             Then he's planning
           to drive to the house

16:49.008 --> 16:52.710
             and load everything
                in the truck.

16:52.712 --> 16:55.880
          And lose it somewhere.

16:55.882 --> 16:59.116
And, uh,
what's to stop him?

16:59.118 --> 17:03.387
              I am, Dr. Bellows.
                     I am!

17:03.389 --> 17:06.924
Mr. Huggins, you may be
an expert on financial matters,

17:06.925 --> 17:10.895
but I happen to be an expert
on Major Anthony Nelson.

17:10.896 --> 17:13.163
   There's no truck.

17:13.165 --> 17:15.165
             [♪♪♪]

17:17.170 --> 17:18.402
       [TIRES SCREECHING]

17:36.422 --> 17:38.121
    ROGER:
Have you driven
a truck before?

17:38.123 --> 17:39.323
        TONY:
        Huh?

17:42.428 --> 17:43.995
               You sure you know
              what you're doing?

17:43.997 --> 17:46.296
    Believe me, Roge,
this is the only way out.

17:49.736 --> 17:51.368
                          Hey...

17:51.370 --> 17:52.436
                 A real Cellini.

17:52.438 --> 17:54.271
Michelangelo.

17:54.273 --> 17:56.240
               Well, he could've
                copied Cellini.

17:56.242 --> 17:58.409
Yeah. Look, let's get
this out first, huh?

17:58.411 --> 17:59.677
                      All right.
Be careful.

17:59.679 --> 18:01.979
It's worth about $2 million.
            Two million dollars?

18:01.981 --> 18:03.514
 Don't drop it.
Come on. Come on.

18:03.516 --> 18:05.449
       All right. Wait a minute,
             wait a minute.

18:05.451 --> 18:07.585
            Whoa, wait a minute.
            I got the heavy end.

18:07.587 --> 18:09.353
I know that.
Come on, let's go.

18:09.355 --> 18:11.121
        Let me turn around here.
                 Wait--

18:11.123 --> 18:13.024
Wait a minute.
I haven't got a good grip on it.

18:13.026 --> 18:15.325
             Okay. I got it.
                I got it.

18:15.327 --> 18:16.928
     Put your end down a minute.
  Hello.

18:16.930 --> 18:19.196
      Hello yourself. Can we get
         this onto the truck?

18:19.198 --> 18:21.899
   Put your end down, Roger.
        I can't let my end down.

18:21.901 --> 18:23.434
 I-I just got a good grip on it.

18:23.436 --> 18:25.870
  Well, get a grip on yourself
     and just put it down.

18:26.672 --> 18:29.173
                [GRUNTING]

18:30.576 --> 18:32.743
       Oh, you sent for help.
             Good idea.

18:32.745 --> 18:34.611
         We can use you.
     Roger--

18:34.613 --> 18:36.413
      We better get this stuff
         out of here before

18:36.415 --> 18:38.782
 the Internal Revenue Department
             catches us.
 This is--

18:38.784 --> 18:40.684
        Give us a hand,
 we'll get this onto the truck.

18:40.686 --> 18:41.752
This is Mr. Huggins.

18:41.754 --> 18:43.120
    Nice to meet you.
      You want to--?

18:43.122 --> 18:44.888
      Of the Department
     of Internal Revenue.

18:46.292 --> 18:48.426
I guess I'd better
be running along.

18:48.428 --> 18:51.228
           Just a moment, major.
               Just a moment.

18:51.230 --> 18:54.765
         We'll consider you
   an accomplice after the fact.

18:54.767 --> 18:55.832
Did you hear what he said?

18:55.834 --> 18:57.268
                   An accomplice
                    after the--

18:57.270 --> 18:59.503
           This is a notice
     of distraint, Major Nelson.

18:59.505 --> 19:01.906
        Nothing is to be removed
           from these premises

19:01.908 --> 19:05.175
           until my assessor
       gets here in the morning.

19:05.177 --> 19:07.144
            Good day, gentlemen.

19:09.114 --> 19:11.682
          Why do you let Jeannie
          do these things to ya?

19:11.684 --> 19:13.350
      Jeannie keeps doing
       these things to me

19:13.352 --> 19:14.485
     because she loves me.

19:14.487 --> 19:15.486
            Yeah, she loves you.

19:16.856 --> 19:18.856
      Well, I guess this time
       you're really trapped.

19:18.858 --> 19:20.123
        Not necessarily.

19:20.125 --> 19:21.525
      How you figure that?

19:21.527 --> 19:24.395
  I'm gonna outsmart her.
  I'm gonna use my brain.

19:24.397 --> 19:25.962
                Yeah, well how
              you gonna do that?

19:25.964 --> 19:28.031
       I'm gonna say,
      "Jeannie, you--"

19:28.033 --> 19:29.600
Hello, master.

19:29.602 --> 19:30.868
      Oh, hello, Jeannie.

19:30.870 --> 19:33.070
Do you like it?
It is a Rembrandt.

19:33.072 --> 19:35.906
  Oh, it's absolutely lovely.
 It's what I've always wanted.

19:35.908 --> 19:37.508
   Oh.
       My own Rembrandt.

19:37.510 --> 19:39.910
You mean you are not going
to ask me to return it?

19:39.912 --> 19:42.279
            No, of course not.
         I wouldn't dream of it.

19:42.281 --> 19:44.114
  Oh, lovely.

19:44.116 --> 19:46.317
       It'll go well with my
  Michelangelo, don't you think?

19:46.319 --> 19:48.118
           Are you--?
   Are you out of your mind?

19:48.120 --> 19:50.921
You realize what's gonna happen
when Huggins finds that picture?

19:50.923 --> 19:52.189
     Well, don't worry about it.

19:52.191 --> 19:54.091
             Don't worry?
             Don't worry.

19:54.093 --> 19:56.093
  Just for that I'm gonna ask
      for separate cells.

19:57.263 --> 19:58.729
            Jeannie,
   I'd like you to get ahold

19:58.731 --> 20:00.731
     of all the old masters
   you can lay your hands on.

20:00.733 --> 20:03.667
Oh, yes, master.
   Oh, uh, wait, wait, wait.

20:03.669 --> 20:07.070
        Now, this is not
 the right surroundings for it.

20:07.072 --> 20:08.405
        Could you--?

20:08.407 --> 20:11.408
       Could you blink
     a villa in Tangiers?

20:11.410 --> 20:14.811
Oh, yes, master.
                  Hey, I get it.

20:14.813 --> 20:15.979
  You'll have your turn next.

20:15.981 --> 20:17.080
    And while you're at it,

20:17.082 --> 20:18.782
    you might as well blink
        all the statuary

20:18.784 --> 20:20.317
       and the paintings
         and everything

20:20.319 --> 20:21.485
   to the Tangiers villa, hm?

20:21.487 --> 20:24.721
You are right, master.

20:24.723 --> 20:26.624
  Oh!
          What is it?

20:26.626 --> 20:28.859
Jeannie, take this with--

20:28.861 --> 20:31.462
  Oh, Mr. Huggins,
I thought you'd gone.

20:31.464 --> 20:34.198
   To tell the truth, I couldn't
      bear to tear myself away

20:34.200 --> 20:35.732
    from these beautiful things.

20:35.734 --> 20:38.101
          So I've decided
   to spend the night here with,

20:38.103 --> 20:41.272
               uh, Michelangelo.

20:41.274 --> 20:42.907
              Oh.

20:42.909 --> 20:44.608
             [♪♪♪]

20:47.647 --> 20:49.646
             [♪♪♪]

20:49.648 --> 20:51.415
        [DOORBELL RINGS]

20:51.417 --> 20:54.751
That must be Professor Preever,
our little art expert.

20:59.158 --> 21:00.257
                    [DOOR OPENS]

21:00.259 --> 21:02.092
   Come in, professor.

21:02.094 --> 21:03.694
              Ah. How do you do?

21:03.696 --> 21:07.130
Can't you, uh, just smell
 the Cellini in the air?

21:07.132 --> 21:08.232
      [LAUGHS]

21:08.234 --> 21:10.767
This is Major Nelson.
             How do you do, sir?

21:10.769 --> 21:12.636
      Major Healey.

21:12.638 --> 21:14.305
    Professor Preever.

21:14.307 --> 21:16.139
                Gentlemen.
        [DOORBELL RINGS]

21:16.141 --> 21:18.775
I'll get it.
                  I'll get it.
                No, I'll get it.

21:18.777 --> 21:20.578
                 Oh, you get it.
             Huh?

21:20.580 --> 21:23.080
        Oh, Dr. Bellows.
 What are you doing here, sir?

21:23.082 --> 21:24.548
                   Hello, major.

21:24.550 --> 21:27.818
    I came to offer my services.
Oh, that's very kind of you.

21:27.820 --> 21:30.087
         You're a lot of things,
         major. A lot of things.

21:30.089 --> 21:32.823
            But you're not
      an international smuggler.

21:32.825 --> 21:34.825
             [♪♪♪]

21:36.128 --> 21:38.061
  I think you're
going to find this

21:38.063 --> 21:40.664
a very exciting morning,
       professor.

21:40.666 --> 21:44.101
For instance, here we have

21:44.103 --> 21:46.970
a genuine Ming vase.

21:53.312 --> 21:55.846
What would you say it was worth?
                    [SNIFFS]

21:55.848 --> 21:58.882
   About a dollar and a quarter.

22:02.121 --> 22:04.755
 "Made in...Japan."

22:04.757 --> 22:06.323
                      I knew it.

22:06.325 --> 22:09.160
              I didn't know how,
                but I knew it.

22:09.162 --> 22:11.328
They have the Renoir.

22:16.869 --> 22:19.136
   With a mustache?

22:19.138 --> 22:21.105
I used to have an aunt
who looked like that.

22:21.107 --> 22:22.273
                [ROGER LAUGHING]

22:23.642 --> 22:25.575
    That wasn't there yesterday.

22:40.026 --> 22:42.026
                    Six fingers?

22:43.830 --> 22:45.629
                This some sort
              of practical joke?

22:45.631 --> 22:46.931
                  You bring me
                all the way here

22:46.933 --> 22:49.900
                and show me
           a collection of junk?

22:49.902 --> 22:52.970
I don't understand.

22:52.972 --> 22:54.939
How 'bout the safe
full of money?

23:00.813 --> 23:02.312
                 [BELLOWS GASPS]

23:10.923 --> 23:13.824
               It's Confederate.

23:13.826 --> 23:16.326
Confederate?

23:16.328 --> 23:18.395
      How--?
How 'bout the gold?

23:20.499 --> 23:23.167
                       [SIGHS]

23:23.169 --> 23:24.601
                       Hm.

23:24.603 --> 23:26.103
                     Try one.

23:32.444 --> 23:34.811
    Chocolate.

23:34.813 --> 23:37.047
          I'll send you my bill.

23:37.049 --> 23:38.849
        BELLOWS: Major--
      HUGGINS: Professor--

23:38.851 --> 23:40.884
just a minute.
                    BELLOWS:
                I can't tell you

23:40.886 --> 23:45.155
what a pleasure it is to see you
     do it to someone else.

23:46.491 --> 23:50.027
    About your trip
to Jamaica, Dr. Bellows,

23:50.029 --> 23:54.264
you did say it was strictly
   government business?

23:54.266 --> 23:59.669
Now, why don't you level with me
 for the rest of the afternoon?

24:00.272 --> 24:02.239
    Whew.

24:03.942 --> 24:05.309
                         Huh?

24:05.311 --> 24:07.110
              Oh. Oh, thank you,
                   Jeannie,

24:07.112 --> 24:08.878
            but I never want
       to go through that again.

24:08.880 --> 24:10.146
 Neither do I.

24:10.148 --> 24:12.382
          Well, it is
    your own fault, master.

24:12.384 --> 24:14.218
                       My fault?
              Yes.

24:14.220 --> 24:16.620
   You should've told me that
 it would get you into trouble.

24:16.622 --> 24:17.787
  I never would've done that.

24:17.789 --> 24:18.955
      There were many ways

24:18.957 --> 24:20.957
     I could have impressed
    that nasty, little man.

24:20.959 --> 24:22.626
           He did not have
       to come into your house.

24:22.628 --> 24:24.628
             [♪♪♪]

24:26.465 --> 24:28.465
             [♪♪♪]
